<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-467-142  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 467 142.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  July 31 1989 n1231* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Harwell creates Profound to offer text retrieval from within IBM'sProfs. (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Harwell Computer Power (product introduction).andO;Product:   IBM 370 (Mainframe computer) (computer programs)ProFound (Search software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Data Base Management SystemsProduct IntroductionText Data BasesSearching.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HARWELL CREATES PROFOUND TO OFFER TEXT RETRIEVAL FROMandM;WITHIN IBM's PROFSandM;Harwell, Oxfordshire-based text retrieval system company HarwellandM;Computer Power, spin-off of the Nuclear research laboratory, has launched aproduct called Profound for users of IBM's Profs office automation system,which runs on 370-type mainframes under VM.andP;  The system offers Profs usersvarious searching techniques throughout the database, enabling them to searchfor concepts, words or phrases by simply typing them in.andP;  Profound alsooffers proximity searching techniques, synonym facilities, truncations andBoolean searches.andP;  Prior to Profound, Harwell claims that Profs users had toleave the system in order to enter a separate text retrieval system.andP;  WithProfound, searching can now be done within the Profs mail and note-logsenvironment.andP;  The system requires a user to have a 2Mb machine so a 9370 isgood enough, running under VM, and itself runs a nucleus extension 512Kb insize, and it costs from #7,000 to #15,000 depending on the size of machine.andO;According to International Data Corp, Harwell's Status text retrieval systemis the UK market leader with a 48% share of the market.andP;  Status was designedby Harwell in its capacity as the UK Atomic Energy Authority.andP;  The systemhas, however, been sold commercially for 10 years, with Harwell ComputerServices being set up two years ago specifically as a marketing arm for theproduct.andP;  The Status text retrieval system can be found searching in suchcorridors of power as the US Pentagon and the Bank of England.andO;</TEXT></DOC>